-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 15 (frame 0-14)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 2
--   Iteration 1: oracle-semantic FAILED (safeDivide argument order)
--     → targeted rewrite fixed code example
--   Iteration 2: all 5 oracles PASSED → gauntlet converged
--
-- Cells evaluated: 15
--   Hard cells: 3 (topic × 1, gauntlet × 2)
--   Soft cells: 12 (explain × 1, 5 oracles × 2, rewrite × 1)
--
-- Oracle breakdown across all frames:
--   oracle-structural: PASS → PASS (format stable)
--   oracle-semantic:   FAIL → PASS (fixed argument order)
--   oracle-factual:    PASS → PASS (facts stable)
--   oracle-stylistic:  PASS → PASS (tone stable)
--   oracle-logical:    PASS → PASS (logic stable)
--
-- Key demonstration:
--   ⊢∘ gauntlet pattern: ANY oracle fails → targeted rewrite → re-run ALL
--   This is the fundamental pattern for multi-dimensional quality control.
--   The gauntlet ensures fixes don't break previously-passing dimensions.
--
-- Confluence note: frames 2-6 (5 parallel-ready oracles) could execute
-- in any order with identical results. Kahn's algorithm guarantees this.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= observation-gauntlet-pattern
  ∴ The multi-oracle gauntlet is a natural Cell pattern: N independent
    oracle cells check different quality dimensions of the same output.
    A crystallized aggregator (⊢= conjunction) determines pass/fail.
    The ⊢∘ loop re-runs ALL oracles after each targeted rewrite,
    ensuring fixes in one dimension don't break another. This is
    analogous to a full regression test suite after a bug fix.

⊢= observation-parallel-oracles
  ∴ All 5 oracle cells depend only on explain→explanation (and optionally
    topic→subject or topic→audience). They share no inter-oracle dependencies.
    Kahn's algorithm places all 5 in the ready set simultaneously. Under
    parallel execution, all 5 could run concurrently — the confluence theorem
    guarantees identical results regardless of scheduling. This is the
    practical payoff of Cell's dataflow model: parallelism for free.

⊢= observation-crystallized-aggregator
  ∴ The gauntlet cell is ▸ crystallized because aggregation is pure logic:
    conjunction of booleans, concatenation of lists, collection of labels.
    No LLM judgment needed. This demonstrates the crystallization boundary:
    oracles are soft (require semantic judgment), but their aggregation is
    hard (deterministic). Verification crystallizes before computation.

⊢= observation-targeted-rewrite
  ∴ The rewrite cell receives failed-oracles[] and failure-report[] from
    the gauntlet. It rewrites ONLY the parts that failed, preserving what
    passed. This is more efficient than full regeneration and prevents
    regression — a fix for a semantic error should not disturb the
    structural format or logical flow. The ⊢∘ re-run of ALL oracles
    verifies this preservation property.

⊢= observation-convergence
  ∴ The gauntlet converged in 2 iterations (of max 5). Iteration 1 found
    one semantic error (safeDivide argument order in Haskell). The targeted
    rewrite fixed exactly that. Iteration 2 verified all 5 dimensions
    pass simultaneously. Fast convergence is expected when (a) the initial
    generation is mostly correct and (b) fixes are targeted rather than
    wholesale rewrites. The max-5 bound prevents infinite loops when
    oracle feedback oscillates or contradicts.
